 from sin, and Aspasia, who represents self-indulgence and sin itself.In the end, The Heathen embodies a profound meditation on the limits of these typecasts: the novel not only explores the restrictions they placed on women during the nineteenth century, but on human happiness, and Poland's then tenuous impulse toward modernity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aWomenzPolandvFiction. 4aFiction & Short Stories. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aSoviet & East European History. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aEast European letters, Narcyza Zmichowska, Polish female writer, George Eliot, nineteenth-century Poland.1 aPhillips, Ursula.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150175776140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501757761423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501757761/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK